# Robot API

You have access to a `robot` object with three methods:

    robot.set_joints(joint_angles)   — Set target joint angles (12-dim numpy array). Does not move the robot.
    robot.step(duration)             — Interpolate from current position to the target over `duration` seconds.
                                       Short duration = fast motion (e.g. 0.2s for a snap/jump).
                                       Long duration = smooth motion (e.g. 3.0s for a gentle transition).
    robot.get_state()                — Returns a dict: {'h': height_m, 'roll': rad, 'pitch': rad, 'x': forward_m, 'y': lateral_m}

Calling set_joints() then step() moves the robot. Call get_state() to read where the robot is.

# Available Primitives

These return 12-dim numpy arrays of joint angles for known poses:

    get_stand_pose()     — standing, body level at ~0.27m height
    get_sit_pose()       — sitting, front legs extended, rear legs tucked
    get_lay_pose()       — laying flat, all legs tucked, body on ground
    get_walk_phases()    — list of 4 joint angle arrays defining one trot gait cycle

You can also construct your own joint angle arrays using numpy if needed.

# Robot Geometry

The Go2 has four legs (FR, FL, RR, RL), each with 3 joints: hip abduction, thigh, calf.
Joint order in the 12-dim array: [FR_hip, FR_thigh, FR_calf, FL_hip, FL_thigh, FL_calf, RR_hip, RR_thigh, RR_calf, RL_hip, RL_thigh, RL_calf].
The robot starts each iteration at its home standing pose (height ~0.27m, body level).

# Reward

After your code runs, the robot's pose is measured:

    R = -(|h - h*| + |roll - roll*| + |pitch - pitch*|)

where h*, roll*, pitch* are target values you are not shown. R = 0 is perfect. Higher (closer to 0) is better.
